		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29527479">I feel that timeskips can be handled as well as any other element in a story. Some storytellers handle them poorly while others are use them effectively. Naruto is the first series that comes to mind as it uses the time skip to power up the characters. Some characters show more growth than others. The biggest problem with this is that the main character didn't learn anything particularly useful during his time training while later in the series he rapidly gains skills. Other characters who gained skills don't advance much past their training during the skip. The biggest thing that gets me angry in Naruto is how Sakura is handled. She's next to useless in the first half and after the timeskip she kicks butt. After one display of her skills she goes back to being largely useless again and barely advances skill-wise. Some timeskips are handled better I'm sure but this was not one of them. <br />
<br />
When judging the timeskip what happens later in the story needs to be taken in to account. if I judged the timeskip shortly after it was executed then I would have said it was fine but now it's looking worse the more I see the characters "power up".</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
