		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message29548293">I think the most common use of timeskipping I observe is the "post-intro" sequence.  For example, in Attack on Titan, we see Eren Jaeger in childhood, watch his emotional trauma as he develops a hatred for the titans, and then timeskip ahead until he's old enough to join the military.  Similarly, in the first volume of Jojo's Bizarre Adventure begins with a childhood sequence where we see Jojo being a chivalrous young lad while Dio is revealed to be a supreme douchebag, and then skip ahead in time until they are both adults attending university.  (I think the 2012 anime adaptation squeezes all of this into the first episode.)<br />
<br />
I believe that good storytelling is about making and fulfilling promises, and a good beginning is one that effectively clues me in to  what kind of story I'm being told.  And if the story begins with the characters as children, there's a risk that the beginning isn't effectively equipping the reader/viewer for what lies ahead.<br />
<br />
However, on a certain level, those two specific examples actually do quite a good job of setting up promises to deliver on later on.  Attack on Titan doesn't begin chronologically, but rather begins with the colossal titan peaking over the wall as the populous watches in terror.  We see the recon corps in action, utilizing their 3D gear to take down a titan.  And <em>then</em>, after the title card, we cut to a young Eren and Mikasa sitting in a field.  The opening clearly conveys that Attack on Titan is an action series about fighting giants, even though the chronology of events begins with the main characters as children.  Similarly, the first scene in Jojo's Bizarre Adventure depicts a ritual sacrifice involving the mask.<br />
<br />
Examples of this can also be found in western media, such as the opening of Star Wars, which begins with a chase in space as the imperial flagship pursues the rebel blockade runner, setting up expectations for a grand adventure-filled space opera even though the protagonist's story begins working as a boy on a farm.<br />
<br />
The other type of timeskip is the "between arc" timeskip, seen in Gurren Lagann (I believe between the second and third arcs), Death Note (halfway point when the series swaps antagonists), and again in Jojo's Bizarre Adventure (between generations of Joestars).  Often, these are mandated by the plot, but I think that they serve the valuable purpose of allowing the characters to have a life outside the story.  In order for characters to feel real and dynamic, they can't just look like paper dolls sculpted solely for the purpose of fitting into the plot.  Real people sometimes go on adventures, but they're usually not thrillseeking 24/7, and often the alternative to timeskipping is crunching a large sequences of events into a perfectly timed sequence of events back-to-back, which can feel cheap in some cases.<br />
<br />
In many ways, I don't view timeskips as inherently good or bad; like with most things, they can be executed properly or improperly.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
